So what ? This is hardly exceptional.

It seems (from a sample of a few dozen matches) that the standard
deviation of the luck as defined by gnubg, is about 200 millipoints/move.

A 9 points match is typically 300-400 moves, for a luck standard deviation
of 3500-4000. Your difference of 7000 against you should happen about 3%
of the time (and when it does, you will almost always lose).

You seem to play quite a lot, so you may well get a few of these unlucky
matches each month on average, and more than one in a given week may not
be outrageous.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is anyone else who plays long matches finding that luck
&gt; determines the outcome against the clearly better player about a
&gt; quarter of the time?
">

There are plenty of web pages giving winning changes for given match
length and rating difference. Try this one for instance :
http://guyfisher.com/workshop/bookmarklets/fibs.html

You'll see that if &quot;clearly better&quot; is a 300-350 rating edge, then, yes,
luck overcomes skill about a quarter of the time in a 9 points match.
