Oh, where to begin?

1.  GNUBG represents a standard that is open source, and therefore one
can use the software and decide whether or not to buy the insurance
offered. While I personally have found flaws with its luck analysis,
that was in singe games, not long matches.  In a long match, if GNUBG
assesses luck as 6.000 or more against someone, few would doubt that
that person got very bad luck relative to his/her opponent.  But those
few could simply not purchase the insurance offered.

2.  If insurance was offered, the site would have to determine that it
would turn a profit in the long term, nothing more.  Of course, they
would need to factor in the cost of software development, etc., but
the point is that is not an issue of sites doing things out of the
goodness or their hearts.

3.  The issue in not that in games with luck players can experience
occasional stretches of very bad luck, but rather whether it is in the
best interest of the site and the &quot;serious&quot; players to implement a
policy that would &quot;smooth out&quot; such stretches, if the site could
profit from it and the player could be assured of not losing too much
within a short period of time against weaker opponents.

4.  Obviously, the site would have to offer luck insurance against a
huge luck difference, or else it would make no sense for either
party.  One idea is to take an average of matches lost against players
GNUBG rated as playing at a lower level, and for each increment of
GNUBG luck factor (perhaps .500), you would be given your money back
for one of the lost matches (assuming all matches are of the same
length, and at least 5 games long).  Perhaps the longer the match, the
lower the increment.
</POST>
